# **Intro** {#intro}

The project will consist of 3 main parts a server on which the control panel will be hosted, a raspberry pi that will relay traffic between peripherals and the control server and the peripherals themselves. Some will be connected directly to the server because they will have to send larger amounts of data. 

The first peripheral will be a mouse which will do keystroke injection. The setup should be transferable between mouses so that it can be adjusted depending on the mouses used in the company. 

The second peripheral will be kali plant so a raspberry pi with kali linux on it to plant into a network and control from the control panel.

Then there will be a network tap this network tap will snoop traffic from a network and send that  traffic to the control panel. It will use tshark to snoop the packets and will forward them to the host. It will also have either an lte modem to connect to the control panel or it will connect to the controller pi’s wifi ap

Lastly there will be evil twin modules that you will be able to spread around the company so devices connect to these ap’s instead of the ones they’re supposed to connect to.

All technical communication will happen over bluetooth, the vpn, ssh and sftp and all other communication will happen over http or https through the netbird tunnel.

void addLog(String message) {

// Mouse power control functions via small signal relay
void powerOnMouse() {  
 digitalWrite(MOUSE\_POWER\_CONTROL\_RELAY\_PIN, HIGH);  // 3.3V energizes relay to supply 5V  
 mousePowered \= true;  
 addLog("Mouse power ON (relay energized - 5V to mouse)");  
 delay(1000); // Give mouse time to initialize and enumerate  
}

void powerOffMouse() {  
 digitalWrite(MOUSE\_POWER\_CONTROL\_RELAY\_PIN, LOW);   // de-energize relay  
 mousePowered \= false;  
 addLog("Mouse power OFF (relay de-energized - no power to mouse)");  
 delay(500); // Brief delay for clean power-down  
}

// Simple Belgian AZERTY keyboard layout mapping  
void typeBelgianAzerty(USBHIDKeyboard\* keyboard, String text) {  
 for (int i \= 0; i \< text.length(); i\++) {  
   char c \= text\[i\];  
    
   // Handle special key sequences  
   if (text.substring(i).startsWith("\<ENTER\>")) {  
     keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_RETURN);  
     keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_RETURN);  
     i \+= 6;  
     continue;  
   }  
   if (text.substring(i).startsWith("\<ESC\>")) {  
     keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_ESC);  
     keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_ESC);  
     i \+= 4;  
     continue;  
   }  
   if (text.substring(i).startsWith("\<TAB\>")) {  
     keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_TAB);  
     keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_TAB);  
     i \+= 4;  
     continue;  
   }  
   if (text.substring(i).startsWith("\<CTRL+C\>")) {  
     keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_LEFT\_CTRL);  
     keyboard\-\>press('c');  
     keyboard\-\>release('c');  
     keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_LEFT\_CTRL);  
     i \+= 7;  
     continue;  
   }  
   if (text.substring(i).startsWith("\<CTRL+V\>")) {  
     keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_LEFT\_CTRL);  
     keyboard\-\>press('v');  
     keyboard\-\>release('v');  
     keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_LEFT\_CTRL);  
     i \+= 7;  
     continue;  
   }  
    
   switch (c) {  
     // Main AZERTY letter swaps  
     case 'a': keyboard\-\>press('q'); keyboard\-\>release('q'); break;  
     case 'A': keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); keyboard\-\>press('q'); keyboard\-\>release('q'); keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); break;  
     case 'q': keyboard\-\>press('a'); keyboard\-\>release('a'); break;  
     case 'Q': keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); keyboard\-\>press('a'); keyboard\-\>release('a'); keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); break;  
     case 'w': keyboard\-\>press('z'); keyboard\-\>release('z'); break;  
     case 'W': keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); keyboard\-\>press('z'); keyboard\-\>release('z'); keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); break;  
     case 'z': keyboard\-\>press('w'); keyboard\-\>release('w'); break;  
     case 'Z': keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); keyboard\-\>press('w'); keyboard\-\>release('w'); keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); break;  
     case 'm': keyboard\-\>press(','); keyboard\-\>release(','); break;  
     case 'M': keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); keyboard\-\>press(','); keyboard\-\>release(','); keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); break;  
      
     // Common punctuation  
     case ',': keyboard\-\>press('m'); keyboard\-\>release('m'); break;  
     case ';': keyboard\-\>press('.'); keyboard\-\>release('.'); break;  
     case '.': keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); keyboard\-\>press('.'); keyboard\-\>release('.'); keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); break;  
     case ':': keyboard\-\>press('/'); keyboard\-\>release('/'); break;  
     case '/': keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); keyboard\-\>press('/'); keyboard\-\>release('/'); keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); break;  
      
     // Numbers and symbols  
     case '&': keyboard\-\>press('1'); keyboard\-\>release('1'); break;  
     case '1': keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); keyboard\-\>press('1'); keyboard\-\>release('1'); keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); break;  
     case '2': keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); keyboard\-\>press('2'); keyboard\-\>release('2'); keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); break;  
     case '"': keyboard\-\>press('3'); keyboard\-\>release('3'); break;  
     case '3': keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); keyboard\-\>press('3'); keyboard\-\>release('3'); keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); break;  
     case '\\'': keyboard\-\>press('4'); keyboard\-\>release('4'); break;  
     case '4': keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); keyboard\-\>press('4'); keyboard\-\>release('4'); keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT); break;  
     case '(': keyboard\-\>press('5'); keyboard\-\>release('5'); break;  
     case ')': keyboard\-\>press('6'); keyboard\-\>release('6'); break;  
     case '\!': keyboard\-\>press('8'); keyboard\-\>release('8'); break;  
      
     // Space and control  
     case ' ': keyboard\-\>press(' '); keyboard\-\>release(' '); break;  
     case '\\n': keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_RETURN); keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_RETURN); break;  
     case '\\t': keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_TAB); keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_TAB); break;  
      
     // Regular letters that don't change  
     default:  
       if (c \>= 'A' && c \<= 'Z') {  
         keyboard\-\>press(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT);  
         keyboard\-\>press(tolower(c));  
         keyboard\-\>release(tolower(c));  
         keyboard\-\>release(KEY\_LEFT\_SHIFT);  
       } else {  
         keyboard\-\>press(c);  
         keyboard\-\>release(c);  
       }  
       break;  
   }  
   delay(10);  
 }  
}

# **Ethernet sniffer** {#ethernet-sniffer}

## **Component Overview** {#component-overview}

Developed a transparent network tap using a Raspberry Pi that sits invisibly between a device and network, capturing all traffic for analysis without any impact on connectivity or performance.

Technical Implementation

### **Core Functionality** {#core-functionality}

The network tap creates a transparent Layer 2 bridge between two Ethernet interfaces, capturing all packets while maintaining full network connectivity. The monitored device remains completely unaware of the tap's presence.

**Key Feature:** Zero network impact \- full gigabit passthrough with \<1ms latency.

### **Architecture** {#architecture}

\[Monitored Device\] ←→ \[eth0 \- Bridge \- eth1\] ←→ \[Network\]  
                              ↓  
                        \[Packet Capture\]  
                              ↓  
                       \[Storage: /var/log/network-tap/\]

### **Technical Components** {#technical-components}

**Network Bridge:**

* Linux bridge utility (`brctl`) for Layer 2 bridging  
* No IP addresses on tap interfaces (ensures transparency)  
* Promiscuous mode for complete packet visibility  
* STP (Spanning Tree Protocol) disabled for minimal latency

**Packet Capture:**

* Wireshark's tshark for professional-grade capture  
* Automatic file rotation with configurable size limits  
* Berkeley Packet Filter (BPF) support for targeted capture  
* PCAP format output (industry standard)

**Remote Access:**

* Netbird mesh VPN for secure remote management  
* SSH-based file retrieval (SCP/SFTP)  
* Separate management interface (WiFi) isolated from tap traffic

**Service Management:**

* Bash script with start/stop/status/restart commands  
* systemd integration for automatic startup  
* Background daemon for continuous capture

## **Problems Solved** {#problems-solved}

### **1\. Network Transparency** {#1.-network-transparency}

**Problem:** The tap must be completely invisible to the victim device.

**Solution:** Implemented Layer 2 bridging with zero IP configuration. No routing, no ARP responses, no DHCP \- the tap operates purely at the data link layer, making it undetectable.

### **2\. Network Isolation** {#2.-network-isolation}

**Problem:** Management traffic must not interfere with captured traffic.

**Solution:** Used three separate interfaces:

* eth0 \+ eth1: Tap interfaces (no IP, bridge only)  
* Wlan0 or usbethernet for lte dongle: Management interface (VPN, SSH access)

Implemented optional policy-based routing with separate routing tables to ensure complete isolation.

### **4\. WiFi Disruption** {#4.-wifi-disruption}

**Problem:** Routing policy setup was breaking WiFi connectivity during testing.

**Solution:** Made routing policy optional and disabled by default. Since tap interfaces have no IP addresses, they're already isolated by design.

### **5\. Cross-Distribution Compatibility (debian based)** {#5.-cross-distribution-compatibility-(debian-based)}

**Problem:** Missing configuration files on some Linux distributions (Kali Linux).

**Solution:** Added automatic creation of required files (`/etc/iproute2/rt_tables`) with proper defaults.

## **Configuration Example** {#configuration-example}

\# Tap interfaces (transparent bridge)  
INTERFACE\_A="eth0"              \# Connected to monitored device  
INTERFACE\_B="eth1"              \# Connected to network

\# Management interface (isolated)  
MANAGEMENT\_INTERFACE="wlan0"    \# For VPN and SSH access

\# Capture settings  
MAX\_CAPTURE\_SIZE="100"          \# 100MB per file  
ROTATE\_CAPTURES="yes"           \# Keep last 10 files  
CAPTURE\_FILTER=""               \# Capture all traffic

## **Usage** {#usage}

\# Start network tap  
sudo network-tap.sh start

\# Check status  
sudo network-tap.sh status

\# Stop network tap  
sudo network-tap.sh stop

# **evil twin aps**  {#evil-twin-aps}

### **Technical Architecture** {#technical-architecture}

The system consists of three integrated components working together:

**1\. ESP32 Microcontroller (Hardware Layer)**

* Dual-mode WiFi operation (AP+STA mode) allowing simultaneous access point hosting and internet connectivity  
* Captive portal web server presenting a convincing login page to connected clients  
* DNS hijacking to redirect all domain queries to the captive portal  
* Network Address Translation (NAT) providing genuine internet access to enhance credibility  
* Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE) GATT server for wireless communication with control systems

### **Key Technical Features** {#key-technical-features}

**Network Address Translation (NAT) & Internet Passthrough** The ESP32 connects to a legitimate WiFi network while simultaneously hosting a fake access point. Using lwIP's NAPT (Network Address and Port Translation) implementation, client traffic is seamlessly routed through the upstream connection. This provides victims with actual internet access, making the attack significantly more convincing and less likely to raise suspicion.

**DNS Hijacking for Captive Portal** The DNS queries for connectivity checks from connected clients are intercepted and redirected to the ESP32's IP address, ensuring that any website the victim tries to visit triggers the captive portal login page. After credential submission, DNS queries are forwarded to Cloudflare DNS (1.1.1.1) to provide normal internet functionality.

### **Technologies Used** {#technologies-used}

* **ESP-IDF Framework**: Professional-grade firmware development for ESP32  
* **lwIP Network Stack**: Lightweight TCP/IP implementation with NAT support  
* **HTTP Server**: Lightweight web server for captive portal interface

### **Technical Challenges Overcome** {#technical-challenges-overcome}

During development, several complex networking issues were resolved:

* There were multiple issues with the evil twin network but they all come down to one think the esp32-s3 does not have a strong enough processor  
* In the first setup i made the esp serve a captive portal locally and connect over ble for management but clients didn’t have internet so this was not a good solution.  
* Then i tried to have internet passthrough in this setup but the cpu was just not strong enough to handle all of this  
* After a while i decided to try to just capture packets instead of serving a captive portal but this also was not possible due to the cpu the captive portal had at most 0.1 mbps which is not usable and noone would connect  
* Finally i decided to put the captive portal on a server and make it available over the internet with a cloudflared tunnel and then just have a very simple redirection page on the esp which works well enough for the poc we get around 8-10 mbps. It also gives us greater control over the captive portal we can now update it way more easily and there is a potential for more advanced phishing pages including mfa.

**Technical Architecture**

The platform implements a microservices architecture with four independent Node.js servers communicating via Socket.IO for real-time bidirectional communication. This way you can control all your plants simultaneously:

* **Main Server (Port 80\)**: Handles Kali Linux device management, authentication, and core functionality  
* **RPI Controller (Port 3002\)**: Dedicated server for the controller pi.  
* **Network Tap Server (Port 3003\)**: Real-time packet capture and network traffic analysis.  
* **Phishing Server (Port 8080\)**: Dynamic phishing page deployment and testing.

**Key Features & Functionality**

*Authentication & Security*

* OpenID Connect (OIDC) integration with Authentik for enterprise-grade authentication  
* Session management with 24-hour token expiration  
* Secure credential handling with environment variable configuration

*Remote Device Management*

* SSH terminal emulation using XTerm.js for browser-based command line access  
* Real-time Nmap network scanning with live progress tracking  
* SFTP file management with upload/download capabilities (100MB limit)  
* Remote command execution with output streaming

*Network Security Tools*

* Live packet capture via tcpdump with BPF filter support  
* Real-time capture statistics and bandwidth monitoring  
* PCAP file management  
* Evil twin access point control for wireless security testing

*Collaborative Features*

* Team notes system for pentester collaboration  
* Real-time credential harvesting from phishing campaigns  
* Centralized logging via Graylog for audit trails  
* Multi-user support with concurrent session handling

**Technology Stack**

*Backend*

* **Runtime**: Node.js with Express.js framework  
* **Real-time Communication**: Socket.IO for WebSocket connections  
* **Authentication**: Passport.js with OpenID Connect strategy  
* **Remote Access**: SSH2 library for secure shell connections  
* **Session Management**: Express-session with secure cookie handling

*Frontend*

* **Terminal Emulation**: XTerm.js with FitAddon for responsive terminals  
* **UI Framework**: Custom CSS with dark theme and responsive design  
* **Real-time Updates**: Socket.IO client for bidirectional communication  
* **Font**: JetBrains Mono for monospace terminal display

*Infrastructure*

* **Containerization**: Docker with docker-compose for multi-service orchestration  
* **Authentication Service**: Authentik (OIDC provider)  
* **Logging Platform**: Graylog with MongoDB and OpenSearch backend  
* **Development Tools**: Nodemon for hot-reload during development

**Technical Challenges & Solutions**

1. **Session Persistence Issue**: Resolved nodemon restarting servers when data files changed, causing session loss. Implemented nodemon configuration to ignore JSON data files while maintaining hot-reload for code changes.

2. **CORS & Cookie Management**: Configured CORS middleware to properly handle credentials and session cookies across different server ports, ensuring seamless multi-server authentication.

3. **Real-time Data Streaming**: Implemented efficient Socket.IO event handling for streaming SSH output, Nmap progress, and packet capture statistics without overwhelming the browser.

4. **Responsive Design**: Created a mobile-friendly interface that adapts terminal sizes and panel layouts for various screen sizes while maintaining functionality.

**Security Considerations**

* All routes protected with authentication middleware except public assets  
* Viewer role restrictions prevent unauthorized command execution  
* Session cookies configured with httpOnly and sameSite flags  
* Environment-based configuration prevents hardcoded credentials  
* Comprehensive logging for audit and compliance requirements

#### **Kali plant** {#kali-plant}

The kali plant is another hardware component but most of its configuration is done through the control panel all you have to do is setup ssh access and the vpn then you can plug it in wherever you want and start pentesting remotely through the control panel. If you want to use vnc you have to also setup the vnc connection to it as described in the documentation guides.

**Deployment & Scalability**

The application uses Docker Compose for simplified deployment with all dependencies (PostgreSQL, Redis, MongoDB, Authentik, Graylog) defined in a single configuration file. Volume mounts enable persistent data storage and hot-reload during development. The modular architecture allows individual servers to scale independently based on load requirements

For authentication i used authentik. This service offers openid configuration and great logging for login attempts, successful login, etc. Its also very easy to add users in authentik and because of the use of openid and [passport.js](http://passport.js) the app is pretty secure.

# **Logging** {#logging}

![][image11]

For logging i use graylog everything that happens on the control panel gets logged and put into graylog this way if something goes wrong or you forget something you’ve done you can always go back and see exactly what happened.
